docs.abstract: From racist graffiti to missed promotions, employees say a “systemic pattern of racial bias” permeates the company.
docs.snippet: From racist graffiti to missed promotions, employees say a “systemic pattern of racial bias” permeates the company.
docs.lead_paragraph: SEATTLE — Last week, Jeff Bezos, Amazon’s chief executive, wrote a rare note to all of the company’s employees. His leadership team had been reflecting on the “systemic racism” facing black communities, he said, and he urged employees to take time to learn and reflect on Juneteenth, the holiday marking the end of slavery in the United States.

headline.main: Amazon Workers Urge Bezos to Match His Words on Race With Actions
headline.print_headline: Race Issues Grow Louder At Amazon

docs.lead_paragraph: KENT, Wash. — After months of being embattled over its response to the coronavirus, Amazon is working to convince the public that its workplaces — specifically, the warehouses where it stores everything from toys to hand sanitizer — are safe during the pandemic.

headline.print_headline: From Warehouses To Office Towers, Virus Remakes The Workplace
